ment and permitting processes High levels of: \u2022 corruption \u2022 inefficiency \u2022 bureaucracy \u2022 political interference \u2022 insecurity Lack of: \u2022 potable water \u2022 proper Sanitation \u2022 open space and parkland \u2022 Flood protection \u2022 Planning and protection against the impacts of climate change High levels of: \u2022 destruction of natural habitat and loss of environmental services \u2022 risk to property and life from natural disasters \u2022 Increase in respiratory infections and diseases affecting productivity Urban Development and Management Systems that are not delivering and maintaining essential urban Infrastructure, land, shelter, and utility services Lack of : \u2022 basic WASH services \u2022 road access \u2022 poor regional transport and logistics systems \u2022 waste and water treatment \u2022 energy to support industry production \u2022 efficient revenue collection systems to cover the costs of service delivery High levels of: \u2022 inefficiency in urban services delivery \u2022 congestion and rising costs in urban services delivery \u2022 inefficiency in the use, maintenance and management of systems and utilities Social Development Systems which are not supporting the social, knowledge , competencies and Learning needs of cities Lack of: \u2022 skills to support the development of the economy \u2022 capacity to used advanced technologies to improve the efficiency of production and supply chain systems \u2022 access to knowledge management systems \u2022 Consideration for human rights, gender and marginalised groups High levels of: \u2022 Migration in search of employment \u2022 unemployment and under utilization of human resources \u2022 violence against women, discrimination in gaining access to employment and political representation Economics and Finance Systems failing to deliver sustainable local economic development, public revenues, create investment and jobs, and reduce poverty Lack of: \u2022 logistics and supply chain systems supporting LED \u2022 micro finance to support LMSSME business investment \u2022 incentives to raise public and private capital and collect taxes to fund the basic provision of economic infrastructure and community services \u2022 capacity to manage and capitalise land and property assets High levels of: \u2022 personal debt \u2022 corruption \u2022 business transaction costs \u2022 dependency on remittances 24 Sustainable and Inclusive Urbanization in Asia Pacific engagement (Figure 3.2). The UN-\u00ad\u2010Habitat Global Campaign on Urban Governance noted that good urban governance is characterized by sustainability, subsidiarity, equity, efficiency; transparency and accountability, civic engagement and citizenship, and security, and that, as is illustrated in the diagram below, these norms are interdependent and mutually reinforcing46. Figure 3.2: UN-\u00ad\u2010Habitat Urban Governance Index47 Source: UN-\u00ad\u2010Habitat 2005. Policy Reforms There are three important policy reform agendas that require change if the challenges of urbanization in the region are to be addressed more effectively. Changing the Anti-\u00ad\u2010urbanization Policies of Governments: Many governments in the region still have strong anti-\u00ad\u2010urban policies. For example, several South Asian countries have only recently embraced the positive benefits of urbanization. Urbanization is often seen by policymakers as a problem rather than the solution to the development of a country. This perspective has also often been reinforced by the anti-\u00ad\u2010urban rhetoric of many international development agencies. Unfortunately, this has held back the development of nations and sub national regions. This strong anti-\u00ad\u2010urban bias is often expressed by rural and regional politicians, conscious of their political power base being eroded as constituents leave for a better future in cities. Winning recognition of urbanization as a positive force in development is still a significant policy challenge in many countries particularly in the Pacific and South Asia. 46 Auclair, C. and A. Jackohango, Good Urban Governance: Towards an Effective Private Sector Engagement. 2009, UN-\u00ad\u2010Habitat, Nairobi. p. 15. 47 UN-\u00ad\u2010Habitat,: Conceptual Foundation and Field Test Report. 2005, Nairobi. p. 97.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ed06b6c2-7425-4e5b-9e75-7c1cf33486be": {"__data__": {"id_": "ed06b6c2-7425-4e5b-9e75-7c1cf33486be", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/strategy-paper-sustainable-and-inclusive-urbanization-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Strategy Paper: Sustainable and Inclusive Urbanization in Asia Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/strategy-paper-sustainable-and-inclusive-urbanization-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "116fc85b2319e2ad74fbd756f57c094d730b300dd710ea2aacac9b08436e6da5"}, "2": {"node_id": "36def8c5-b2e6-4b54-a5b5-e4fb154a32df", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/strategy-paper-sustainable-and-inclusive-urbanization-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7718f9ce1b029b4dfab9f688fb3b393d71f3164108874341c051734c49f83a39"}}, "hash": "b381a756ad79ee72cd0a99721b1394e943ab38f3c5a60365154c4ba1a0a1a3a6", "text": "2005, Nairobi. p. 97. URBAN GOVERNANCE IN